<TITLE> 'Iron hand' against militants: Sahara </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 21 (bdnews24.com)Home minister Sahara Khatun told parliament Thursday that her government come down with an 'iron hand' against militant activities. While delivering a statement on urgent issues, the home minister said the Awami League government would go after those involved in stockpiling arms and ammunition to deteriorate law and order. Sahara Khatun made the statement following the arrest of 12 people whom the minister termed as the leaders and activists of Bangladesh Jamaat-e-Islami and student wing Islami Chhatra Shibir. "The police arrested 12 people with firearms, 37 rounds of bullets, gun powder, splinters and books on jihad. Of the four guns, three revolvers are made in Pakistan and the other in the US. ," Khatun told parliament referring to the arrests in Chittagong on Jan 18. "We will not allow terrorism, militant and destructive activities to take place anymore," said Sahara. "We must contain them with an iron hand no matter who are involved," she said. The minister said the arms and ammunitions that were recovered at a building in the Double Mooring area of Chittagong with a view to hamper the government's efforts. "The motive of stockpiling the arms and ammunition is to hamper the government's initiative to try war criminals and execution of the death penalties in the Bangbandhu murder case," said Sahara. She said the Jamaat-e-Islami and its associated student body Islami Chhatra Sangha were involved in the massacre of millions of people, including intellectuals, and rape of 200,000 women during Bangladesh's War of Independence in 1971.
